<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-840-657  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 840 657.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IEEE Spectrum  Dec 1990 v27 n12 p71(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Keithley's phantom repeater.andM;</TITLE><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Among the technological developments during World War II was theintroduction of the driven-shield technique for making measuringinstruments with high-input impedances.andP;  This technique proved tobe valuable to the modern semiconductor industry.andP;  Joseph F.andO;Keithley designed an instrument that used the driven-shieldprinciple to offer a high-input impedance, three parallel outputsand a choice of three fixed gains.andP;  Because the phantom repeatercontained no proprietary circuits, and was based on work doneelsewhere, no patent was issued for the instrument.andP;  The phantomrepeater was only mildly successful on the commercial market.andP;  Itsreal importance was to stimulate interest in high-impedancemeasuring.andP;  The driven-shield approach is used by most wafertesters in Silicon Valley.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Measurement TechniquesMeasurementProduct DevelopmentPatentTestingSilicon ValleyHistory.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>